==============================================================
COSMOLOGY BRANCH OF THE CURVATURE–MEMORY THEORY
Derived from the action with interaction term b T M^2
==============================================================

Author: Martin Ollett
Year: 2026


--------------------------------------------------------------
1. ACTION
--------------------------------------------------------------

We begin with the covariant action

    S = ∫ d^4x √(-g) [
            R/(16πG)
          - 1/2 g^{μν} ∂_μ M ∂_ν M
          - a M^4 / 4
          + b T M^2
          + L_b
        ].

Here

    M(x)   = curvature–memory scalar
    a      = quartic self-interaction
    b      = coupling to the matter trace
    T      = T^μ_μ of the baryonic matter sector
    L_b    = baryonic matter Lagrangian.

For pressureless dust,

    T = -ρ_b.

So the interaction term becomes

    b T M^2 = - b ρ_b M^2.


--------------------------------------------------------------
2. FRW BACKGROUND
--------------------------------------------------------------

Take a spatially flat FRW spacetime

    ds^2 = -dt^2 + A(t)^2 δ_{ij} dx^i dx^j

with Hubble rate

    H = Ȧ / A.

Assume homogeneous background fields

    M(t,x) = M̄(t)
    ρ_b(t,x) = ρ̄_b(t).

The background scalar-field equation is

    M̈̄ + 3H Ṁ̄ + a M̄^3 + 2 b ρ̄_b M̄ = 0.

For dust,

    ρ̄_b(a_cos) = ρ_b0 a_cos^(-3).


--------------------------------------------------------------
3. EFFECTIVE POTENTIAL
--------------------------------------------------------------

The homogeneous scalar evolves in the effective potential

    V_eff(M) = a M^4 / 4 - b T M^2.

For dust,

    T = -ρ_b

so

    V_eff(M) = a M^4 / 4 + b ρ_b M^2.


--------------------------------------------------------------
4. PHYSICALLY VIABLE SIGN CHOICE
--------------------------------------------------------------

The cosmologically interesting branch is

    b < 0.

Write

    b = - |b|.

Then

    V_eff(M) = a M^4 / 4 - |b| ρ_b M^2.

This has matter-supported minima rather than a stable origin.


--------------------------------------------------------------
5. MATTER-SUPPORTED MINIMUM
--------------------------------------------------------------

The extrema satisfy

    dV_eff/dM = a M^3 - 2 |b| ρ_b M = 0.

Thus either

    M = 0

or

    a M^2 = 2 |b| ρ_b.

The nonzero minima are

    M_*^2 = 2 |b| ρ_b / a.

Hence the physically relevant background branch is

    M_*(a_cos) = ± sqrt( 2 |b| ρ_b(a_cos) / a ).

Since

    ρ_b ∝ a_cos^(-3),

the minimum drifts as

    M_* ∝ a_cos^(-3/2).


--------------------------------------------------------------
6. CURVATURE OF THE POTENTIAL AT THE MINIMUM
--------------------------------------------------------------

The second derivative of the effective potential is

    d²V_eff/dM² = 3 a M^2 - 2 |b| ρ_b.

Evaluated at the minimum,

    M = M_*,

one finds

    m_*^2 = 4 |b| ρ_b.

Thus perturbations around the matter-supported minimum are stable and
have a positive matter-dependent mass.


--------------------------------------------------------------
7. BACKGROUND ENERGY DENSITY AND PRESSURE
--------------------------------------------------------------

The scalar energy density and pressure are

    ρ̄_M = 1/2 Ṁ̄^2 + a M̄^4 / 4 + b ρ̄_b M̄^2

    p̄_M = 1/2 Ṁ̄^2 - a M̄^4 / 4 - b ρ̄_b M̄^2.

On the b < 0 branch this means the matter coupling contributes
nontrivially to both background density and pressure.


--------------------------------------------------------------
8. FRIEDMANN EQUATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------

The background expansion is governed by

    3H^2 = 8πG ( ρ̄_b + ρ̄_M )

    2Ḣ + 3H^2 = -8πG ( p̄_b + p̄_M ).

For dust,

    p̄_b = 0.


--------------------------------------------------------------
9. ANALYTIC BACKGROUND SOLUTIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------

9.1 Matter-dominated era

Using N = ln a_cos, the homogeneous field equation becomes

    M'' + (3/2) M'
        + (a/H^2) M^3
        + (3b/(4πG)) M
        = 0.

In the weak-amplitude linearized regime this reduces to

    M'' + (3/2) M' + μ^2 M = 0

with

    μ^2 = 3b/(4πG).

This gives

    M(a_cos) = C_+ a_cos^(r_+) + C_- a_cos^(r_-)

where

    r_± = -3/4 ± sqrt(9/16 - μ^2).

For weak coupling one mode decays rapidly, while one mode decays
very slowly.


9.2 Quartic-dominated regime

If the quartic term dominates,

    a M^2 >> 2 |b| ρ_b,

then the field obeys approximately

    M̈ + 3H Ṁ + a M^3 = 0.

In the oscillatory quartic regime,

    ρ_M ∝ a_cos^(-4)
    M_amp ∝ a_cos^(-1).

So the quartic branch behaves like radiation.


9.3 Late-time Hubble-frozen regime

At late times, if Hubble friction dominates,

    3H Ṁ >> a M^3,

then

    3H Ṁ + a M^3 ≈ 0

which integrates to the slow decay law

    M(t) ∝ t^(-1/2).

Thus a nonzero background field can survive and evolve only very
slowly at late times.


--------------------------------------------------------------
10. LINEAR PERTURBATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------

Perturb in Newtonian gauge:

    ds^2 = -(1+2Ψ) dt^2 + A(t)^2 (1-2Φ) δ_{ij} dx^i dx^j.

Expand

    M(t,x) = M̄(t) + δM(t,x)

    ρ_b(t,x) = ρ̄_b(t) + δρ_b(t,x).

The linearized scalar equation is

    δM̈ + 3H δṀ
    + (k^2/A^2 + 3 a M̄^2 + 2 b ρ̄_b) δM
    =
    Ṁ̄ ( Ψ̇ + 3 Φ̇ )
    - 2 a M̄^3 Ψ
    - 2 b ρ̄_b M̄ Ψ
    - 2 b M̄ δρ_b.

Unlike the earlier higher-order overlap choice, the matter density
perturbation now sources δM directly at linear order.


--------------------------------------------------------------
11. PERTURBATIONS ABOUT THE MATTER-SUPPORTED MINIMUM
--------------------------------------------------------------

For b < 0, the physically relevant expansion is

    M = M_* + χ

where M_* is the matter-supported minimum.

The minimum shifts under a density perturbation as

    δM_* = (M_*/2) δ_b

where

    δ_b = δρ_b / ρ̄_b.

The fluctuation mass on this branch is

    m_*^2 = 4 |b| ρ̄_b.

In the subhorizon quasi-static regime,

    χ ≈ [ m_*^2 / (k^2/A^2 + m_*^2) ] δM_*.

Thus the scalar perturbation tracks matter perturbations with a
Yukawa-like screening factor.


--------------------------------------------------------------
12. LEADING-ORDER GROWTH MODIFICATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

On the minimum branch, the leading effective memory-density
perturbation is

    δρ_M = β_*(k,a_cos) δρ_b

with

    β_*(k,a_cos)
      ≈ - (8 |b|^3 / a)
          ρ̄_b(a_cos)^2
          / (k^2/A^2 + 4 |b| ρ̄_b(a_cos)).

Equivalently,

    β_*(k,a_cos)
      ≈ - B(a_cos)
          [ κ_M^2(a_cos) / (k^2 + κ_M^2(a_cos)) ]

where

    B(a_cos)    = (2 |b|^2 / a) ρ̄_b(a_cos)

    κ_M^2(a_cos) = 4 |b| ρ̄_b(a_cos) A^2.

This is negative for all positive a and |b|, so the theory predicts

    G_eff < G

and therefore suppressed growth.


--------------------------------------------------------------
13. MODIFIED POISSON EQUATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

The subhorizon Poisson equation becomes

    (k^2/A^2) Φ = 4πG ( δρ_b + δρ_M )
                = 4πG [1 + β_*(k,a_cos)] δρ_b.

Thus

    G_eff(k,a_cos) = G [ 1 + β_*(k,a_cos) ].


--------------------------------------------------------------
14. LINEAR GROWTH EQUATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

The baryon growth equation in cosmic time is

    δ̈_b + 2H δ̇_b
      = 4π G_eff(k,a_cos) ρ̄_b δ_b.

Using N = ln a_cos and primes for d/dN, this becomes

    δ'' + [ 2 + d ln H / dN ] δ'
      =
      (3/2) Ω_b(a_cos)
      [ 1 + β_*(k,a_cos) ]
      δ.

This is the first directly testable linear-growth prediction of the
theory.


--------------------------------------------------------------
15. LIMITING REGIMES OF GROWTH
--------------------------------------------------------------

15.1 Large scales

If

    k^2/A^2 << 4 |b| ρ̄_b

then

    β_* ≈ - (2 |b|^2 / a) ρ̄_b.

So large-scale growth experiences maximal suppression.


15.2 Small scales

If

    k^2/A^2 >> 4 |b| ρ̄_b

then

    β_* ≈ - (8 |b|^3 / a) ρ̄_b^2 / (k^2/A^2)

so

    β_* → 0.

Thus GR is recovered on sufficiently small scales.


15.3 Redshift dependence

Since

    ρ̄_b ∝ a_cos^(-3),

the suppression evolves with time:

    • earlier times: stronger raw coupling but stronger screening
    • later times: weaker raw coupling but less screening

Qualitatively this gives a late-time, scale-dependent growth
suppression.


--------------------------------------------------------------
16. GROWTH INDEX
--------------------------------------------------------------

Define the growth rate

    f = d ln δ / d ln a = δ'/δ.

Then

    f' + f^2 + [ 2 + d ln H/dN ] f
      =
      (3/2) Ω_b(a_cos) [ 1 + β_*(k,a_cos) ].

Using the usual ansatz

    f ≈ Ω_m(a_cos)^γ

the theory predicts

    γ(k,a_cos) > γ_LCDM ≈ 0.55

on the b < 0 branch, with the largest deviation on large scales
where β_* is most negative.

So the memory theory predicts a scale-dependent increase in the
growth index and therefore a suppression of clustering.


--------------------------------------------------------------
17. COSMOLOGY–GALAXY LINK
--------------------------------------------------------------

The same background field that controls cosmological growth also
controls the galaxy transition scale.

The effective galaxy acceleration scale satisfies

    g_†^2 ∼ (a/|b|) M̄^3

schematically, so the slowly evolving background memory amplitude
feeds directly into

    • the RAR transition scale
    • the BTFR normalization
    • the late-time growth suppression.

Thus the theory has a coherent multiscale structure:

    cosmological background M̄(a)
        ↓
    linear growth modification G_eff(k,a)
        ↓
    nonlinear galaxy transport
        M^3 ∝ g_b g_obs.


